box}}\n{{Indianapolis Colts starting quarterback navbox}}\n\n{{Portal bar|American football|Biography|College football}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orlovsky, Dan}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American people of Slavic descent]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:ESPN people]]\n[[Category:Houston Texans players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Colts players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Rams players]]\n[[Category:People from Shelton, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Buccaneers players]]\n[[Category:UConn Huskies football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n|image=Dan Orlovsky.JPG\n|image_size=260px\n|caption=Orlovsky with the Tampa Bay Buccaneers\n|number=9, 6, 7, 8\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|mf=yes|1983|8|18}}\n|birth_place=[[Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 5\n|weight_lbs = 215\n|high_school = [[Shelton High School (Connecticut)|Shelton (CT)]]\n|college=[[UConn Huskies football|Connecticut]]\n|draftyear=2005\n|draftround=5\n|draftpick=145\n|pastteams=\n* [[Detroit Lions]] ({{NFL Year|2005}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2008}})\n* [[Houston Texans]] ({{NFL Year|2009}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2010}})\n* [[Indianapolis Colts]] ({{NFL Year|2011}})\n* [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] ({{NFL Year|2012}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2013}})\n* Detroit Lions ({{NFL Year|2014}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})\n* [[Los Angeles Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2017}})*\n|pastteamsnote=yes\n|statlabel1=Passing attempts\n|statvalue1=512\n|statlabel2=Passing completions\n|statvalue2=298\n|statlabel3=Percentage\n|statvalue3=58.2\n|statlabel4=[[Touchdowns|TD]]\u2013[[Interceptions|INT]]\n|statvalue4=15\u201313\n|statlabel5=Passing yards\n|statvalue5=3,132\n|statlabel6=[[Passer rating]]\n|statvalue6=75.3\n|nfl=ORL645634\n}}\n\n'''Daniel John Orlovsky''' (born August 18, 1983) is a former [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who played thirteen seasons in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and a football analyst for [[ESPN]]. He was drafted by the [[Detroit Lions]] in the fifth round of the [[2005 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at the [[UConn Huskies football|University of Connecticut]]. Orlovsky also played for the [[Houston Texans]], [[Indianapolis Colts]], [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], and [[Los Angeles Rams]].\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], Orlovsky played [[high school football]]. \"When I was younger, I would have garbage cans set up all around the yard,\" Orlovsky recalled. \"And I would have like 20 balls and just fire them into the cans. I really had nothing else to do back then.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.yourct.com/sportsnews/1912/ |title=The Passer: Dan Orlovsky state's best QB |last=Agostino |first=David |publisher=YourCT.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511050451/http://www.yourct.com/sportsnews/1912/ |archive-date=May 11, 2008 |access-date=March 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOrlovsky attended [[Shelton High School (Connecticut)|Shelton High School]] and became the starting quarterback during his sophomore year.<ref>[http://www.freep.com/article/20081013/SPORTS01/810130352/1049 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016090229/http://www.freep.com/article/20081013/SPORTS01/810130352/1049 |date=October 16, 2008 }}</ref>  As a senior, he threw for 2,489 yards and 58 touchdowns as the Gaels went 12\u20130, winning the state championship. His overall record as a high school quarterback was 28\u20134. He earned [[All-American]] honors from Prep Football Report, SuperPrep and Prep Star, and was also named Connecticut all-state, Class LL MVP, the [[New Haven Register]]'s Connecticut Player of the Year and winner of the McHugh Award. {{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iwasallstate.com/FallSports/Football/FootballAllStateTeams/2000s/2000/tabid/116/Default.aspx |title=2000 New Haven Register All-State Football Team |publisher=Iwasallstate.com |date= |accessdate=March 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDespite offers from [[Purdue]] and [[Michigan State]], Orlovsky committed to play at Connecticut, where he wanted the challenge of elevating the Huskies into a Big East contender.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}\n\n==College career==\nOrlovsky became the starter during his freshman year when [[Keron Henry]] suffered a sprained knee.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.courant.com/2001-10-23/features/0110230073_1_south-florida-dan-orlovsky-uconn-coach-randy-edsall |title=Uconn Passes Job To Orlovsky |last=Price |first=Terry |date=October 23, 2001 |work=[[Hartford Courant]] |access-date=August 26, 2011}}</ref> Orlovsky threw for 1,379 yards and nine touchdowns on 128 of 269 passing (47.6 percent) while being intercepted 11 times.<ref>{{cite news |title=Connecticut Huskies |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/college/2002/preview/uconn/ |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |year=2002 |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nStarting every game as a sophomore, Orlovsky hit on 221 of 366 attempts (60.4 percent), with 19 touchdowns and 11 interceptions. His 2,488 yards passing rank fourth on the school's season-record list.\n\nAs a junior, he ranked seventh in the nation in passing, hitting on 279 of 475 passes (58.7 percent) for 3,485 yards, 33 touchdowns and 14 interceptions. His 33 scoring tosses ranked first in the NCAA Division I-A.\n\nOrlovsky did not match his 2003 figures as a senior, but guided the team to victory in its inaugural bowl appearance. He gained 3,354 yards with 23 touchdowns and 15 interceptions on 288 of 456 throws (63.0 percent) in 2004.\n\nOrlovsky holds the school record for most pass completions (916), pass attempts (1,567), yards passing (10,706), touchdown passes (84), interceptions (51), total plays (1,710) and total yards (10,421).\n\nOrlovsky, along with head coach [[Randy Edsall]], served as the \"face\" of the UConn football program durings the early 2000s.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121105040604/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-15118604.html HighBeam]</ref>  Orlovsky was the starting quarterback during the Huskies transitional period from [[Division I-AA]] football, to independent [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] team, to full-fledged member of the [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]].\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Detroit Lions===\nWhen [[Jeff Garcia]] went down with an injury in the '05 preseason, Orlovsky emerged as the Lions' primary backup. He played in two regular season contests in 2005, including the nationally televised [[Thanksgiving]] Day game against the [[Atlanta Falcons]]. In the two contests combined, Orlovsky completed 7-of-17 passes for 63 yards, with no touchdowns or interceptions.\n\nPrior to the 2006 season the Lions traded [[Joey Harrington]] and released [[Jeff Garcia]], while signing [[Jon Kitna]] and [[Josh McCown]]. Orlovsky spent the 2006 season as the third-string QB. Orlovsky was projected to be the second-string quarterback in 2007 because [[Drew Stanton]], who was picked in the second round of the [[2007 NFL Draft]], was placed on [[injured reserve]]; however, the Lions acquired [[J. T. O'Sullivan]], who bumped Orlovsky back to third on the depth chart. Orlovsky did not take a regular season snap in either 2006 or 2007; in 2008, O'Sullivan went to the [[San Francisco 49ers]] and emerged as the starting QB there.\n\nOn September 15 against the [[Green Bay Packers]], he finished the game, completing two of four attempts for six yards.\n\nOrlovsky made his first career NFL start on October 12, 2008, in a 12\u201310 Lions loss against the [[Minnesota Vikings]]. He completed 12 of 21 passes for 150 yards, with one touchdown and no turnovers.  However, early in the first quarter when he lined up in shotgun formation, he inadvertently ran out of the back of his own end zone for a safety, in what turned out to be the margin of victory.<ref>[http://www.nfl.com/videos?videoId=09000d5d80b8de5f Orlovsky ran out of the back of his own end zone]</ref>  \"When they started blowing the whistle, I was like, 'Did we false start, or were they offsides or something?'\" Orlovsky said. \"And I looked, and I was just like, 'You're an idiot.'\"<ref>[http://www.freep.com/article/20081013/SPORTS01/810130352/1049 Orlovsky red-faced, but confident in Lions.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016090229/http://www.freep.com/article/20081013/SPORTS01/810130352/1049 |date=October 16, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn the following week of the Lions' winless season, Orlovsky connected with [[Calvin Johnson]] on a 96-yard touchdown pass.\n\nOrlovsky also started the final game of the 2008 season, but was unable to lead his team to their first victory of the season. Orlovsky announced his intention to explore the free agent market at the end of the 2008 season rather than accept a contract as a backup quarterback in Detroit.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090223/ap_on_sp_fo_ne/fbn_lions_orlovsky;_ylt=Aiy.5Fw845COb6IBEy81r2cLMxIF Orlovsy Plans to Enter Free Agency] Yahoo Sports, February 23, 2009</ref>\n\n===Houston Texans===\n[[File:Dan Orlovsky - Houston Texans.jpg|175pcpx|thumbnail|right|Orlovsky during his tenure with the Texans.]]\nHe signed with the [[Houston Texans]] for a 3-year, $9 million deal on March 1, 2009. He was beaten out by [[Rex Grossman]] for the backup quarterback position during the preseason, and served as the Texans number three quarterback.  After the 2009 season, Grossman signed a one-year contract with the [[Washington Redskins]], making Orlovsky the backup quarterback for the Texans.\n\n===Indianapolis Colts===\nHe signed with the [[Indianapolis Colts]] as a free agent on July 30, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2011-nfl-free-agency/2011/7/29/2304398/dan-orlovsky-released-cut-houston-texans |title=Dan Orlovsky To Sign With Colts, According To Report |last=Larrabee |first=Brandon |date=2011-07-29 |website=SBNation.com |access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref> He was one of the final cuts as NFL teams trimmed their rosters to 53. The Colts later resigned Orlovsky on September 27, 2011. He was named the starter over the benched [[Curtis Painter]] on November 30, 2011. The next week, Orlovsky went on to complete 30 of 37 passes, with 353 yards, 2 touchdowns, and 1 interception, for a total passer rating of 113.1 in his first start as a Colt against the [[New England Patriots]], in a 31\u201324 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/967975-dan-orlovsky-nearly-leads-colts-on-what-would-have-been-greatest-comebacks-ever |title=Dan Orlovsky Nearly Leads Colts on What Would Have Been a Great Comeback |last=Smith |first=Eric |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\nOn December 18, 2011, Orlovsky and the Colts won their first game of the season (after starting 0\u201313) against the Titans. Coincidentally, the last time the Colts won was also against the Titans in January of the previous season. This was Orlovsky's first official win as a starter in the NFL. On December 22, 2011, Orlovsky led the Colts on a 12-play, 78-yard drive in a comeback victory over the 10\u20134 Houston Texans with less than two minutes remaining in the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.colts.com/news/a-stirring-victory-for-colts-6664387?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=A STIRRING VICTORY FOR COLTS |website=www.colts.com |language=en-US |access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n===Tampa Bay Buccaneers===\nOn March 15, 2012, the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] signed Orlovsky to a two-year-contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/7690116 |title=Bucs sign QB Orlovsky to be Freeman's backup |date=2012-03-15 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref> On April 4, 2013, Orlovsky was cut by the Buccaneers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sessler|first=Marc|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000157518/article/dan-orlovsky-dj-ware-cut-by-tampa-bay-buccaneers|title=Dan Orlovsky, D.J. Ware cut by Tampa Bay Buccaneers|publisher=[[National Football League]]|date=April 4, 2013|accessdate=April 4, 2013}}</ref> On April 8, 2013, four days after being cut, Orlovsky re-signed with the Buccaneers.\n\n===Detroit Lions (second stint)===\nOn April 2, 2014, the Lions signed Orlovsky as their backup quarterback to [[Matthew Stafford]].<ref>[http://www.detroitlions.com/news/lions-insider/article-1/TWENTYMAN-Lions-find-their-backup-quarterback-in-Dan-Orlovsky/d8afcb08-a40d-4fca-bcad-2788faf5f51f TWENTYMAN: Lions find their backup quarterback in Dan Orlovsky] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404205500/http://www.detroitlions.com/news/lions-insider/article-1/TWENTYMAN-Lions-find-their-backup-quarterback-in-Dan-Orlovsky/d8afcb08-a40d-4fca-bcad-2788faf5f51f |date=April 4, 2014 }} Detroit Lions, April 2, 2014</ref> On March 2, 2015, the Lions re-signed Orlovsky to a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.detroitlions.com/news/lions-insider/article-1/Lions-re-sign-quarterback-Dan-Orlovsky/84c01eb7-f1b3-47a4-a3ea-881a93cdf0ff |title=Lions re-sign quarterback Dan Orlovsky |work=[[Detroit Lions]] |first=Tim |last=Twentyman |date=March 2, 2015 |accessdate=March 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150304035206/http://www.detroitlions.com/news/lions-insider/article-1/Lions-re-sign-quarterback-Dan-Orlovsky/84c01eb7-f1b3-47a4-a3ea-881a93cdf0ff |archive-date=March 4, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In a game against the Cardinals, Orlovsky came in for a struggling Matthew Stafford, and threw for 191 yards, a touchdown, and an interception. \n\nOn March 11, 2016, the Lions re-signed Orlovsky as their primary backup quarterback to Stafford.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.detroitlions.com/news/news-short/article-1/Lions-re-sign-QB-Dan-Orlovsky/f05f2573-258e-493f-90fb-073993f163e0 |title=Lions re-sign QB Dan Orlovsky |work=Detroit Lions |date=March 11, 2016 |accessdate=March 11, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312061156/http://www.detroitlions.com/news/news-short/article-1/Lions-re-sign-QB-Dan-Orlovsky/f05f2573-258e-493f-90fb-073993f163e0 |archive-date=March 12, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Rams===\nOn July 20, 2017, Orlovsky signed with the [[Los Angeles Rams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000821031/article/rams-agree-to-terms-with-qb-dan-orlovsky |title=Dan Orlovsky, Los Angeles Rams agree on contract |last=Sessler |first=Marc |date=July 20, 2017 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> He was released by the Rams on September 2, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.therams.com/news-and-events/article-1/Rams-Announce-Roster-Moves/33a04e1d-a581-47b1-a2ef-75984001a240 |title=Rams Announce Roster Moves |last=Han |first=Jamie |date=September 2, 2017 |website=TheRams.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208051619/http://www.therams.com/news-and-events/article-1/Rams-Announce-Roster-Moves/33a04e1d-a581-47b1-a2ef-75984001a240 |archive-date=February 8, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nOrlovsky announced his retirement from football on October 11, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|work=ESPN.com|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/detroit-lions/post/_/id/31265/dan-orlovsky-known-for-taking-safety-while-chased-by-jared-allen-retires|title=Dan Orlovsky, known for taking safety while chased by Jared Allen, retires|date=October 11, 2017|first=Michael|last=Rothstein|accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref> He joined [[ESPN]] as an analyst.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.prideofdetroit.com/2018/7/11/17558382/report-dan-orlovsky-to-join-espn-nfl-ncaa-coverage-television-analyst |title=Report: Dan Orlovsky to join ESPN\u2019s NFL, NCAA coverage |last=Reisman |first=Jeremy |date=2018-07-11 |website=Pride Of Detroit |access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n===NFL reg